properties.NAME: Chief Justice's Chamber & Office
properties.DESCRIPTION: The Chief Justice worked in three interconnecting rooms: Courtyard One, the Chief Justice's Chambers and Office. He presided in Courtroom One and conducted his administrative duties in his Chambers and Office. The first Chief Justice of independent Singapore was Chief Justice (CJ) Wee Chong Jin, the first Asian in a 155-year line of British chief justices. The last Chief Justice to occupy these rooms was CJ Yong Pung How, who held his position from 1990 to 2006. The key highlight of the Chambers and Office is their furniture. They were specially designed for this space and produced locally, hand carved by Singapore-based craftsmen trained in British workmanship.

properties.NAME: City Hall Chamber
properties.DESCRIPTION: Completed in 1929, City Hall Chamber was the grandest room in the Municipal Building and the whole of Singapore then. It was used by the Municipal commissioners as a venue for meetings and official functions pertinent to the development of Singapore. On 12 September 1945, Japanese forces surrendered to the Allied Forces in this Chamber, officially ending the Japanese Occupation of Singapore.  Singapore's first Prime Minister, Lee Kuan Yew, and his cabinet were sworn into office here on 5 June 1959 and 19 October 1963. Other national leaders who have been sworn in here include former President Yusof bin Ishak and former Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong.

properties.NAME: City Hall Foyer
properties.DESCRIPTION:
An OUTBOUND commission by National Gallery Singapore

Forum for Drone Speech – Singapore Simulations is inspired by the Gallery’s architecture and its connections to Singapore’s colonial past and diasporic society. The installation alludes to European neo-classical architecture, drawing on its forms to create a conversation with the former Municipal Building (now City Hall Wing). This historic building witnessed many of the nation’s milestones, including its eventual proclamation of independence in 1965.

The labels on the faux marble structure playfully appropriate museological language, interweaving factual introductions of artefacts with Yang’s subjective readings of them. The viewer needs to match these labels with images ranging from Dora Gordine’s multi-ethnic bronze busts, which were first displayed at this site, to works relating to the building's history by Italian sculptor Rudolfo Nolli, and various instruments used to navigate and perceive the world.

Three sculptures by Yang here appear as incongruous as the selection of artefacts, combining traditional crafts with modern industrial processes and materials. They are displayed as static museum pieces yet evoke movement and sound through bells and turbine vents, while recordings of birdsong and a speech by humanoid robot Nadine in six languages play from two loudspeakers.

Forum for Drone Speech – Singapore Simulations expresses a sense that history and the present are in flux. The illusory qualities of the materials used, including faux marble, hologram prints and robotic voice, suggest that different realities are at play. This work creates an awareness of museums as spaces where objects are continually rearranged and reinterpreted to envision alternative narratives, provoking questions on identity, belongingness and engagement.

properties.NAME: Holding Cells
properties.DESCRIPTION: Defendants were held in these holding cells between the time they were brought to Supreme Court and when their trial begun. Police vans, commonly knows as "Black Marias" , transported defendants to Supreme Court from remand centres. Defendants were then escorted into the building via the rear entrance. A series of suspended steel corridors, a portion of which has been preserved, led directly from the cells to the four original courtrooms. You can view where the corridor that led to Courtroom 3 emerged. In the past, there were 12 jail cells: two for women and ten for men. Two of the holding cells have been preserved and can now accessed at the first level of the Supreme Court Wing. The Courtroom is now Gallery 7 of the UOB Southeast Asia Gallery.

properties.NAME: National Kitchen by Violet Oon
properties.DESCRIPTION: Helmed by local celebrity chef Violet Oon, National Kitchen is a celebration of fine local flavours reflecting Singapore’s colourful culinary heritage. Dine indoors in an elegant dining hall or enjoy sweeping views of Singapore’s skyline with local bar bites and sunset cocktails on the veranda.

properties.NAME: Ng Teng Fong Roof Garden Gallery
properties.DESCRIPTION: The Ng Teng Fong Roof Garden Gallery is a living, breathing outdoor space where artists present a site-specific work reflecting on South-east Asia's heritage and histories from a contemporary perspective.

Ngee Ann Kongsi Auditorium
properties.DESCRIPTION: Nestled in the basement of the City Hall Wing, the Ngee Ann Kongsi Auditorium features a theatre seating layout with tiered seating, a fully-equipped stage and state-of-the-art audio visual equipment. There is an accompanying foyer where guests can network, relax and savour deletable culinary offerings.

properties.NAME: Odette
properties.DESCRIPTION: This modern French restaurant reflects Chef-Owner Julien Royer’s respect for seasonality, terroir and the finest artisanal produce. Using classic French techniques, Royer presents the world’s finest seasonal ingredients in their purest form and flavour.

properties.NAME: Padang Atrium
properties.DESCRIPTION: The Padang Atrium sits between the former City Hall and Supreme Court buildings. During the day, natural light streams in, highlighting the sculptural canopy made from golden filigree metal and glass. At night, atmospheric lighting enhances  the grand architectural features and six-storey high tree-like columns.

properties.NAME: Padang Deck
properties.DESCRIPTION: Located on the rooftop of the City Hall Wing, this open-air space offers spectacular, panoramic views of Singapore’s skyline, making this a suitable venue for elegant alfresco events.

properties.NAME: Rotunda Library & Archive
properties.DESCRIPTION:
Situated in the heart of the former Supreme Court, where the legal reference library was once located, the Rotunda Library & Archive offers visitors a gateway to the Gallery’s extensive collection of reference and archival materials focusing on 19th to 20th century art of Singapore and Southeast Asia, and provides a welcoming environment for reading and research.

The Library & Archive collection consists of approximately 20,000 archival and nearly 10,000 reference materials. Of these, the archives consist of artists’ primary resources such as letters, writings, interviews, recordings of performances, sketches and drawings, as well as press clippings and other exhibition-related ephemera. The resources continue to grow thanks to the generous support of artists and their families, collectors and other collaborators.

properties.NAME: Seminar Rooms
properties.DESCRIPTION:
The Gallery’s modern seminar rooms are flexible and can be tailored to the requirements of any event. 
Air-conditioned and purpose-built, they offer a comfortable space for discussions.

properties.NAME: Singapore Courtyard
properties.DESCRIPTION: This unique and spacious courtyard is set in the middle of the former City Hall building, which first housed the Municipal Council and later, the offices of various ministries including the Prime Minister’s Office.

properties.NAME: Supreme Court Balcony
properties.DESCRIPTION: The Supreme Court Historical Balcony overlooks the iconic view of Singapore’s skyline. Steeped in history, its imposing columns were designed by Italian sculptor, Rudolfo Nolli, who also designed the building’s tympanum which symbolises justice.

properties.NAME: Supreme Court Historical Lobby (Foundation Stone)
properties.DESCRIPTION: On 1 April 1937, the foundation stone of Supreme Court was laid 195 feet under the Main Dome by the Governor of the Straits Settlements, Sir Shenton Thomas. Buried beneath the stone was a cylindrical brass casket containing six Straits Settlements newspapers published on 31 March 1937 and some Straits Settlements coins. This time capsule is due to be retrieved in the year 3000. The headlines of the newspapers in the capsule highlighted the concerns of the period: the tense global situation surrounding the rearmament of Europe, bitter industrial strife on rubber estates, the problem of mui tsai (female slaves) and the uncertain outlook for two commodities vital to the Malayan economy - rubber and tin.

properties.NAME: Supreme Court Terrace
properties.DESCRIPTION: Built around the former Supreme Court’s Rotunda dome, old and new architecture merge perfectly in this captivating space. The terrace offers a sophisticated setting for events such as product launches, private receptions and seated dinners.

properties.NAME: Supreme Court Terrace Steps to Level 4
The Gallery Store By ABRY
properties.DESCRIPTION: One of the finest multi-label boutiques in Singapore - The Gallery Store by Abry offers exciting, thoughtful, and innovative range of museum and art-related merchandise and publications. It is operated by Abry Pte Ltd, an award-winning distributor and retailer of luxury and premium lifestyle brands, and champion of empowerment and social impact.

properties.NAME: The Great Mischief
properties.DESCRIPTION:
Find The Great Mischief at the National Gallery and discover a European-style bistro by day - expect hearty brunch and lunch options, kid-friendly favourites, and the perfect complements of fresh bakes and coffee.

Come sunset, guests will enter a gastronomical realm of Catalunya with an element of surprise – a fine array of authentic hot and cold tapas, classic starters like Patatas Bravas with a twist for the senses, before a show stopping Paella.

Save room for Churros and a slice of the all-time favourite Burnt Cheesecake. Top off the night from the dry bar with a tipple of non-alcoholic wine, champagne and cava.

properties.NAME: The Spine Hall
properties.DESCRIPTION:
Spark Your Imagination at The Spine Hall 

Designed as an open space, The Spine Hall hosts a rotation of large-scale artworks and multi-disciplinary programmes that visitors may easily observe or interact with. 

Within The Spine Hall are Y-Lab, an art and tech convergence product innovation lab, with two dedicated rooms: the Showcase, which exhibits an exciting rotation of innovation prototypes developed under Y-Lab’s partnerships and Foundry programme; and the Workspace, which provides a dynamic sandbox environment for entrepreneurs and their mentors to test ideas – from brainstorms to product demonstrations.

properties.NAME: Y-Lab
properties.DESCRIPTION: Y-Lab is a unique Art x Tech convergence product innovation lab of National Gallery Singapore. This Y-Lab Showcase space displays a rotation of innovation prototypes. Such prototypes allow visitors to be part of the experiment and participate in co-creation by experiencing projects early, turning the space into a “living lab” that encourages dialogue among the public.
